2026-03-10 | Count Subarrays Where First Element is Minimum

	Question
Return the number of subarrays whose first element is the minimum element.

	Approach
1.	For every index i,
		find the **next element to the right that is smaller than arr[i]**.
2.	If the next smaller element appears at index j,
		then valid subarrays starting at i can extend only until j−1.
3.	Therefore number of valid subarrays starting at i:
		j − i
4.	If no smaller element exists,
		then it extends to the end:
		n − i
5.	Use a **monotonic increasing stack** to compute the next smaller element efficiently.

	Time Complexity
	O(n)

	Space Complexity
	O(n)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    long long countSubarrays(vector<int>& arr) {
        int n = arr.size();
        stack<int> st;
        vector<int> nextSmaller(n, n);

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            while (!st.empty() && arr[i] < arr[st.top()]) {
                nextSmaller[st.top()] = i;
                st.pop();
            }
            st.push(i);
        }

        long long ans = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            ans += nextSmaller[i] - i;
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

	Key Insight
A subarray starting at index **i** remains valid until we encounter an element **smaller than arr[i]**.  
Finding the **next smaller element** allows us to count all such subarrays in **O(n)** time using a monotonic stack.
